# IMport lobster data

lobster_abundance <- read_csv(here::here("data", "lobster_abundance.csv"), na = "-99999") %>%
  clean_names()
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   DATE = col_character(),
##   SITE = col_character(),
##   TRANSECT = col_double(),
##   REPLICATE = col_character(),
##   SIZE_MM = col_double(),
##   LOBSTER_COUNT = col_double()
## )

Use the tidyr::uncount() function to expand a frequency variable

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>%
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Yay! Now each lobster has its own row. This is tidy format.

Lets look at this a bunch of ways:

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x =  site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site), width = 0.2)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x =  site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_violin(aes(color = site))
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x = size_mm)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = site)) +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(sample = size_mm)) +
  geom_qq() +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free", (size = 0.5))
